Creative gaming¶

Game telemetry dataset used for the Creative Gaming: Propensity-to-Buy Modeling case

Feature descriptions¶

  • converted: Purchased the Zalon campain ("yes" or "no")
  • GameLevel: Highest level of game achieved by the user
  • NumGameDays: Number of days user played the game in last month (with or without network connection)
  • NumGameDays4Plus: Number of days user played the game in last month with 4 or more total users (this implies using a network connection)
  • NumInGameMessagesSent: Number of in-game messages sent to friends
  • NumFriends: Number of friends to which the user is connected (necessary to crew together in multiplayer mode)
  • NumFriendRequestIgnored: Number of friend requests this user has not replied to since game inception
  • NumSpaceHeroBadges: Number of "Space Hero" badges, the highest distinction for gameplay in Space Pirates
  • AcquiredSpaceship: Flag if the user owns a spaceship, i.e., does not have to crew on another user's or NPC's space ship ("no" or "yes")
  • AcquiredIonWeapon: Flag if the user owns the powerful "ion weapon" ("no" or "yes")
  • TimesLostSpaceship: The number of times the user destroyed his/her spaceship during gameplay. Spaceships need to be re-acquired if destroyed.
  • TimesKilled: Number of times the user was killed during gameplay
  • TimesCaptain: Number of times in last month that the user played in the role of a captain
  • TimesNavigator: Number of times in last month that the user played in the role of a navigator
  • PurchasedCoinPackSmall: Flag if the user purchased a small pack of Zathium in last month ("no" or "yes")
  • PurchasedCoinPackLarge: Flag if the user purchased a large pack of Zathium in last month ("no" or "yes")
  • NumAdsClicked: Number of in-app ads the user has clicked on
  • DaysUser: Number of days since user established a user ID with Creative Gaming (for Space Pirates or previous games)
  • UserConsole: Flag if the user plays Creative Gaming games on a console ("no" or "yes")
  • UserHasOldOS: Flag if the user has iOS version 10 or earlier ("no" or "yes")
  • training: Dummy variable that splits the dataset into a training (1) and test (0) dataset

PART I¶

The question "What is the probability of organically converting to Zalon?" refers to the likelihood that a player of a Free-to-Play (F2P) mobile video game will choose to purchase or subscribe to a specific package or feature within the game, in this case, referred to as "Zalon," without being influenced by paid advertising or direct marketing efforts. Instead, this "organic conversion" implies the player decides to make the purchase based on their natural engagement and experience with the game.

Question 1¶

In [4]:
# Question 1.1 
# What is the probability of organically converting to Zalon? (1 point)
train = cg_organic[cg_organic['training'] == 1]
test = cg_organic[cg_organic['training'] == 0]

q1 = train[train['converted'] == 'yes'].shape[0] / train.shape[0]

print(f'The organic probability of converting to Zalon is {round(q1*100, 4)}%')

The organic probability of converting to Zalon is 5.6476%

This result helps us confirm that the statement made in the 'creative-gaming.pdf' file is accurate.

"In the two months since the release, only 5.75% of active players had purchased the campaign."

# numeric variables

numeric_stats.loc['missing'] = train.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).apply(lambda x: x.isnull().sum()) 
numeric_stats.loc['nunique'] = train.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).apply(lambda x: x.nunique()) 

# non-numeric variables
non_numeric_stats = train.describe(include=[object, 'category'])  
non_numeric_stats.loc['missing'] = train.select_dtypes(include=[object, 'category']).apply(lambda x: x.isnull().sum())

non_numeric_stats.loc['most_common'] = train.select_dtypes(include=[object, 'category']).apply(lambda x: x.value_counts().idxmax())  
non_numeric_stats.loc['least_common'] = train.select_dtypes(include=[object, 'category']).apply(lambda x: x.value_counts().idxmin())

In comparing two logistic regression models designed to predict user conversion in a gaming context, both demonstrate similar explanatory power with McFadden's Pseudo R-squared values of 0.184, suggesting they effectively capture the variance in conversion rates. The models differ primarily in their complexity; Model 1 opts for a more streamlined approach, focusing on key variables such as game level, acquisitions, and purchases, while Model 2 incorporates additional variables including user behavior details like 'TimesKilled' and operating system use. Despite this difference, both models show low multicollinearity among predictors and good predictive ability, with an Area under the ROC Curve (AUC) of 0.82 for Model 2.

Question 2.1

Generate prediction plots for each of these 5 features and summarize your findings (1 point)

The following plots seem to show the highest impact:

  • NumSpaceHeroBadges: The plot shows a steep upward curve, indicating a strong positive relationship between the number of Space Hero badges a player has and the probability of the predicted outcome. This suggests that players with more badges are significantly more likely to convert.

  • AcquiredSpaceship: There's a noticeable jump in the probability of the predicted outcome for players who have acquired a spaceship, indicating that this feature is a strong predictor of conversion.

  • NumFriends: The plot indicates a positive relationship between the number of friends a player has and the probability of the predicted outcome, with a steep increase as the number of friends grows. This feature is likely a significant predictor of the outcome.

  • NumFriendRequestIgnored: This plot shows a negative relationship between the number of friend requests ignored a player has and the probability it will convert. This is an interesting finding, since it could suggest that social interactions, or the lack of them, are goof predictor in the user's behavior.

# You have finished building a logistic regression model to predict what kind of Space Pirates gamers were more or less likely to purchase the Zalon campaign. After debriefing Mi Haruki on the performance of the predictive model, she lays out the next steps:
# “We will test the effectiveness of the in-app ad and the predictive model by exposing a random 150,000 customers to a 2-week ad campaign and measuring their conversion to Zalon over the next 2 months. At the same time, we will randomly pick another 30,000 customers and observe their organic upgrade behavior over the same period. 
# This set of customers will not be served any in-app ads.

# loading the data - this dataset must NOT be changed
cg_organic_control = pd.read_parquet("data/cg_organic_control.parquet")
rsm.md("data/cg_organic_control_description.md")
cg_organic_control.head()

# I want you to compare three groups based on this data.

# Group 1: The randomly picked 30,000 Space Pirates gamers who did not receive in-app ads during the experimental period.
# Group 2: A randomly picked 30,000 Space Pirates gamers among the 150,000 who were served in-app ads for Zalon.
# Group 3: A model-selected 30,000 Space Pirates gamers among the 120,000 (after taking out Group 2) who were served in-app ads for Zalon.

# Please report back to me how well the ads are working in terms of conversion rates and profits and by how much the model improves these metrics, all based on targeting 30,000 customers. To calculate profits, please use revenues of $14.99 from selling Zalon. The cost of serving ads to a consumer for 2 weeks is $1.50 in lost coin purchases.”

Creative gaming¶

Game telemetry dataset used for the Creative Gaming: Propensity-to-Buy Modeling case

Feature descriptions¶

  • converted: Purchased the Zalon campain ("yes" or "no")
  • GameLevel: Highest level of game achieved by the user
  • NumGameDays: Number of days user played the game in last month (with or without network connection)
  • NumGameDays4Plus: Number of days user played the game in last month with 4 or more total users (this implies using a network connection)
  • NumInGameMessagesSent: Number of in-game messages sent to friends
  • NumFriends: Number of friends to which the user is connected (necessary to crew together in multiplayer mode)
  • NumFriendRequestIgnored: Number of friend requests this user has not replied to since game inception
  • NumSpaceHeroBadges: Number of "Space Hero" badges, the highest distinction for gameplay in Space Pirates
  • AcquiredSpaceship: Flag if the user owns a spaceship, i.e., does not have to crew on another user's or NPC's space ship ("no" or "yes")
  • AcquiredIonWeapon: Flag if the user owns the powerful "ion weapon" ("no" or "yes")
  • TimesLostSpaceship: The number of times the user destroyed his/her spaceship during gameplay. Spaceships need to be re-acquired if destroyed.
  • TimesKilled: Number of times the user was killed during gameplay
  • TimesCaptain: Number of times in last month that the user played in the role of a captain
  • TimesNavigator: Number of times in last month that the user played in the role of a navigator
  • PurchasedCoinPackSmall: Flag if the user purchased a small pack of Zathium in last month ("no" or "yes")
  • PurchasedCoinPackLarge: Flag if the user purchased a large pack of Zathium in last month ("no" or "yes")
  • NumAdsClicked: Number of in-app ads the user has clicked on
  • DaysUser: Number of days since user established a user ID with Creative Gaming (for Space Pirates or previous games)
  • UserConsole: Flag if the user plays Creative Gaming games on a console ("no" or "yes")
  • UserHasOldOS: Flag if the user has iOS version 10 or earlier ("no" or "yes")

from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score

# Filter the DataFrame for 'rnd_30k' == 0 and extract the relevant columns
filtered_data = cg_ad_treatment[cg_ad_treatment['rnd_30k'] == 0]
y_true = filtered_data['converted'] == "yes"  # Assuming 'converted' contains "yes" for positive cases
y_scores = filtered_data['pred_logit']

# Calculate AUC
auc_score = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_scores)

# Print the calculated AUC
print("AUC:", auc_score)

# Question 3.6
# 6. Why would CG have collecting data for group 1 (cg_organic_control) given that they already had data on organic conversions from the cg_organic data? (2 points)

CG collected data for group 1 (cg_organic_control) despite having data on organic conversions from the cg_organic data to establish a baseline for comparison. This allows for the accurate assessment of the impact of any interventions by comparing changes in the control group with those in experimental groups, ensuring any observed differences in organic conversions can be attributed directly to the interventions.
